### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

forms

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

If the model depends on a required `input`, the forms webmcp tool, is responsible for throwing `NG0950: Input "id" is required but no value is available yet.` 

Repro: 

```ts
describe('App', () => {
  @Component({
    selector: 'app-root',
    template: ``,
  })
  class App {
    id = input.required<string>();
    model = linkedSignal(() => ({id: this.id()}));

    form = form(this.model, () => {}, {
      experimentalWebMcpTool: {
        description: 'foo',
        name: 'foo',
      },
    });
  }

  it('should work', async () => {
    TestBed.configureTestingModule({providers: [provideExperimentalWebMcpForms()]});
    const fixture = TestBed.createComponent(App);
  });
});
```

### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

platform-server

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

The fix for GHSA-68x2-mx4q-78m7 added a guard in `@angular/core` that throws `NG0401` (Missing Platform) when `bootstrapApplication()` is called server-side without a `BootstrapContext`. The guard checks `globalThis.ngServerMode`:

```javascript
// @angular/core/fesm2022/core.mjs ~line 2420
if (typeof ngServerMode !== 'undefined' && ngServerMode && !platformRef) {
  throw new RuntimeError(-401, 'Missing Platform...');
}
```

The guard only fires when `ngServerMode === true`. The problem is that `platformServer()` in `@angular/platform-server` sets this flag to `true` at the start of a render but then resets it back to `undefined` inside an `onDestroy` callback when the platform is destroyed at the end of each render:

```javascript
// @angular/platform-server/fesm2022/_server-chunk.mjs lines 576-588
function platformServer(extraProviders) {
  const noServerModeSet = typeof ngServerMode === 'undefined';
  if (noServerModeSet) {
    globalThis['ngServerMode'] = true;
  }
  const platform = createPlatformFactory(platformCore, 'server', INTERNAL_SERVER_PLATFORM_PROVIDERS)(extraProviders);
  if (noServerModeSet) {
    platform.onDestroy(() => {
      globalThis['ngServerMode'] = undefined;  // resets the guard flag after every render
    });
  }
  return platform;
}
```

After any `renderApplication()` call completes (which internally calls `platformServer()` and then `asyncDestroyPlatform()`), the `onDestroy` callback fires and `ngServerMode` is back to `undefined`. The guard condition `typeof ngServerMode !== 'undefined' && ngServerMode` evaluates to `false`, so subsequent calls to `bootstrapApplication()` without a `BootstrapContext` pass through silently and Angular bootstraps in browser mode inside a Node.js process.

This affects deployments that run outside the Angular CLI build pipeline. When built through the CLI, `@angular/build`'s esbuild plugin replaces the bare `ngServerMode` identifier with the compile-time constant `true` across all bundle output, so `noServerModeSet` is always `false` and the `onDestroy` branch is dead code. But when TypeScript is transpiled by tsx, ts-node, Vite SSR, esbuild without the Angular-specific define plugin, or NestJS's own build process, `ngServerMode` is read and written as a live runtime global on `globalThis`. In these environments the reset happens on every render cycle.

I have already reported this to the Google VRP team.

## Reproduction

The server file below is the complete reproduction. Run it with `npx tsx server-poc.ts`. No build step.

All output shown in this report was captured from this server running locally.

### src/tokens.ts

```typescript
import { InjectionToken } from '@angular/core';
export const REQUEST_AUTH_TOKEN = new InjectionToken<string>('REQUEST_AUTH_TOKEN');
export const REQUEST_USER_ID    = new InjectionToken<string>('REQUEST_USER_ID');
```

### src/app/app.ts (minimal component, inline template required for JIT outside CLI)

```typescript
import { Component, inject } from '@angular/core';
import { REQUEST_AUTH_TOKEN, REQUEST_USER_ID } from '../tokens';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  imports: [],
  template: `<p>user: {{ userId }}</p><p>token: {{ authToken }}</p>`,
})
export class App {
  protected userId    = inject(REQUEST_USER_ID,    { optional: true }) ?? 'anonymous';
  protected authToken = inject(REQUEST_AUTH_TOKEN, { optional: true }) ?? 'NO_TOKEN';
}
```

### src/app/app.config.ts

```typescript
import { ApplicationConfig } from '@angular/core';
export const appConfig: ApplicationConfig = { providers: [] };
```

### src/app/app.config.server.ts

```typescript
// provideServerRendering() is intentionally absent.
// If included, it calls globalThis['ngServerMode'] = true at module evaluation
// time without registering an onDestroy, which prevents the reset from happening.
// The real-world tsx/Vite/NestJS pattern does not call provideServerRendering()
// from module scope — it calls renderApplication() per request, which internally
// calls platformServer(), which is where the onDestroy is registered and the
// reset occurs.
import { mergeApplicationConfig, ApplicationConfig } from '@angular/core';
import { appConfig } from './app.config';

const serverConfig: ApplicationConfig = { providers: [] };
export const config = mergeApplicationConfig(appConfig, serverConfig);
```

### src/server-poc.ts

```typescript
import '@angular/compiler';
import express from 'express';
import { renderApplication } from '@angular/platform-server';
import { bootstrapApplication } from '@angular/platform-browser';
import { App } from './app/app';
import { config } from './app/app.config.server';
import { REQUEST_AUTH_TOKEN, REQUEST_USER_ID } from './tokens';

const BASE_URL    = 'http://localhost:4000';
const HTML_DOC    = `<!doctype html><html><head></head><body><app-root></app-root></body></html>`;
const RENDER_OPTS = { document: HTML_DOC, url: `${BASE_URL}/`, allowedHosts: ['localhost'] as string[] };

const server = express();

function liveFlag(): unknown { return (globalThis as Record<string, unknown>)['ngServerMode']; }

server.get('/poc/status', (_req, res) => {
  const mode = liveFlag();
  res.json({
    ngServerMode:     mode ?? null,
    type:             typeof mode,
    guardArmed:       mode === true,
    bypassWindowOpen: typeof mode === 'undefined',
    timestamp:        new Date().toISOString(),
  });
});

server.get('/poc/render', async (req, res) => {
  const userId = (req.query['userId'] as string) || 'anonymous';
  const token  = (req.query['token']  as string) || 'no-token';

  const before = liveFlag();
  let during: unknown;

  const html = await renderApplication(
    (ctx) => {
      // platformServer() runs before bootstrap() is called.
      // Reading the flag here captures its value mid-render.
      during = liveFlag();
      return bootstrapApplication(App, config, ctx);
    },
    {
      ...RENDER_OPTS,
      platformProviders: [
        { provide: REQUEST_AUTH_TOKEN, useValue: token },
        { provide: REQUEST_USER_ID,    useValue: userId },
      ],
    }
  );

  const after = liveFlag();
  res.setHeader('X-ngServerMode-Before', String(before));
  res.setHeader('X-ngServerMode-During', String(during));
  res.setHeader('X-ngServerMode-After',  String(after));
  res.setHeader('X-Bypass-Window-Open',  String(typeof after === 'undefined'));
  res.send(html);
});

server.get('/poc/legacy-bypass', async (_req, res) => {
  const modeAtCall = liveFlag();
  try {
    const appRef = await bootstrapApplication(App, config);  // no BootstrapContext
    appRef.destroy();
    res.json({ result: 'BYPASS_SUCCESS', guardFired: false, ngServerModeWas: String(modeAtCall) });
  } catch (err: unknown) {
    const e = err as Error;
    const isGuard = e.message?.includes('NG0401') || e.message?.includes('Missing Platform');
    res.json({
      result:          isGuard ? 'BYPASS_BLOCKED' : 'GUARD_BYPASSED_BROWSER_MODE_EXECUTED',
      guardFired:      isGuard,
      guardBypassed:   !isGuard,
      ngServerModeWas: String(modeAtCall),
      error:           e.message?.substring(0, 300),
      explanation:     !isGuard
        ? 'NG0401 was NOT thrown. Angular bootstrapped in browser mode on the server. ' +
          'The error above is a downstream consequence (no DOM in Node.js), not the guard. ' +
          'Root cause: platformServer().onDestroy resets ngServerMode to undefined ' +
          '(@angular/platform-server/fesm2022/_server-chunk.mjs lines 583-585).'
        : 'Guard fired correctly. Call /poc/render first to open the bypass window.',
    });
  }
});

server.listen(4000, () => console.log('listening on http://localhost:4000'));
```

### Steps to reproduce

```
cd your-angular-22-project
npm install express @angular/compiler tsx
npx tsx src/server-poc.ts
```

Then in a second terminal, run these requests in order:

```
curl http://localhost:4000/poc/status
curl -s -D - -o /dev/null "http://localhost:4000/poc/render?userId=alice&token=ALICE_JWT_SECRET_TOKEN"
curl http://localhost:4000/poc/status
curl http://localhost:4000/poc/legacy-bypass
```

### Actual output (captured live, Angular 22.0.0, tsx 4.22.4)

**Step 1 — Status at server startup (no render has happened yet)**

```
GET /poc/status
{"ngServerMode":null,"type":"undefined","guardArmed":false,"bypassWindowOpen":true,"timestamp":"2026-06-09T07:10:13.504Z"}
```

**Step 2 — A normal SSR render**

```
GET /poc/render?userId=alice&token=ALICE_JWT_SECRET_TOKEN

Response headers:
X-ngServerMode-Before : undefined
X-ngServerMode-During : true
X-ngServerMode-After  : undefined
X-Bypass-Window-Open  : true
```

`During` is `true` because `platformServer()` set the flag synchronously before calling bootstrap. `After` is `undefined` because `asyncDestroyPlatform()` ran the `onDestroy` callback. The guard window is open.

**Step 3 — Status confirmed after render**

```
GET /poc/status
{"ngServerMode":null,"type":"undefined","guardArmed":false,"bypassWindowOpen":true,"timestamp":"2026-06-09T07:10:31.026Z"}
```

**Step 4 — bootstrapApplication without BootstrapContext (should throw NG0401, does not)**

```
GET /poc/legacy-bypass
{
  "result": "GUARD_BYPASSED_BROWSER_MODE_EXECUTED",
  "guardFired": false,
  "guardBypassed": true,
  "ngServerModeWas": "undefined",
  "error": "document is not defined",
  "explanation": "NG0401 was NOT thrown. Angular bootstrapped in browser mode on the server. The error above is a downstream consequence (no DOM in Node.js), not the guard. Root cause: platformServer().onDestroy resets ngServerMode to undefined (@angular/platform-server/fesm2022/_server-chunk.mjs lines 583-585)."
}
```

`guardFired: false` confirms NG0401 was not thrown. `error: "document is not defined"` is Angular executing browser-mode bootstrap code in Node.js — exactly what the guard was introduced to prevent. The guard did not fire because `ngServerMode` was `undefined` at the time of the call, having been reset by the previous render's `onDestroy` callback.

## Affected versions

Angular 22.0.0. The same code is present in earlier versions. Any version that introduced the `BootstrapContext` guard as a fix for GHSA-68x2-mx4q-78m7 is affected, because the `onDestroy` reset was part of the same code change and undermines the guard in non-CLI build environments.

## Root cause

`@angular/platform-server/fesm2022/_server-chunk.mjs` lines 583-585:

```javascript
platform.onDestroy(() => {
  globalThis['ngServerMode'] = undefined;
});
```

This callback is registered once per `platformServer()` call where `ngServerMode` was not already set. It fires when `asyncDestroyPlatform()` destroys the platform at the end of every `renderApplication()` cycle. After it fires, `ngServerMode` is `undefined` and the NG0401 guard in `@angular/core` no longer triggers for the rest of the process lifetime, unless another render arms it again — only for it to be reset again afterward.

## Suggested fix

Do not reset `ngServerMode` to `undefined` in the `onDestroy` callback. If the intent is to allow a process to serve both SSR and non-SSR contexts, the flag should remain `true` for the duration of the process. Alternatively, track armed state with a counter or a persistent boolean that is never set back to `undefined` once the server platform has been initialized.

A one-line fix in `_server-chunk.mjs`:

```javascript
// Remove or no-op the onDestroy reset:
platform.onDestroy(() => {
  // globalThis['ngServerMode'] = undefined;  <-- remove this
});
```



